The area had experienced a shutdown of services as residents were protesting against the incorporation of their area into Lim345 municipality a new municipality administered in Malamulele.On Monday several schools re-opened while businesses were also operating.The provincial department of education said it was still assessing the backlog in order to come up with strategies to ensure that pupils in the area were on par with others in schools throughout the province and country.Departmental spokesman Naledzani Rasila urged pupils to return to school so that they did not lag behind in terms of their syllabus. Education is a societal issue and requires of us to work together to ensure pupils do not lose any more time said Rasila.He said stakeholders including pupils teachers and parents welcomed the move to allow learning and teaching to resume.Arnold Mulaudzi chairman of the Pro-Makhado Task Team said they appreciated the intervention of Vha-Venda king Toni Mphephu Ramabulana who approached President Jacob Zuma to make sure the situation was normalised in Vuwani. We will work together with the leadership of government to ensure that things get back to normal in Vuwani. And we appreciate the role played by King Mphephu Ramabulana to ensure tensions are defused in the area Mulaudzi said.Meanwhile seven people have been arrested in connection with the violence that occurred in Vuwani on Sunday. Police spokesman Brigadier Motlafela Mojapelo said the arrested people aged between 18 and 31 were charged with public violence and malicious damage to property.He said those arrested would appear in the Vuwani Magistrate's Court soon .- TMG Digital/SowetanLIVE